To schedule an #rstats script in Windows 7: 1) map UNC path to a drive, eg W: 2) in my.R, double path separators; 3) in Task Scheduler Action, give the UNC path to run.bat; 4) in run.bat, add first Rscript.exe to PATH (if not there yet), and then "Rscript.exe W:\somedir\my.R"

Result: This short analysis exposed two potential bugs and one optimization. Leading to a ~50% reduction of unnecessary work in my colleagues prototype and our database #rstats #datadriven pic.twitter.com/NKkTaYujTh

After a quick followup with him: One of those SQL statements can reduced to one query and caching results. The other two statements shouldn't be queried that often! Now we are going after these; leading to two bug tickets. #rstats #datadriven

In a prev. thread I identified one user in one database (guy with prototype) to create nearly all log entries. Now I found out, over 55% of his entries are created by only 3 different kinds of SQL statements. Two of those are always exactly the same! #rstats #datadriven
Counting the statements and plotting the top 10 of them created the following plot. The top 3 SQL statements created ~55% of all log entries! #rstats #datadriven pic.twitter.com/qlQeu23HDr

After that I cleaned the logged SQL statements a bit. I used regular expressions to replace numbers with a <number> token, and removed strings with '<string>'. This way, I aggregate SQL patterns instead of certain statements, differing in just one number. #rstats #datadriven
It was a very interesting experience firstly seeing this as an unusual pattern and then digging through the data until everything makes sense. #rstats #datadriven

Further investigation showed it wasn't really a thing. At 2017-10-26 I tested different ways to store serialized data (~ 22 KB) in a single field. Next week, the colleague using his prototype software (producing lots and lots of entries) was out of office. #rstats #datadriven

This plots shows the created log entries over time. No one of us was able to explain the peak around end of October, and why the logs over time broke in the days after this peak. #rstats #datadriven pic.twitter.com/KJNPBudvzi
I've further analysed the before mentioned MariaDB Audit Log. There where some funny results. #rstats #datadriven
